Context management is the #1 thing that makes an IDE agent feel “senior” instead of random. The best architecture is tiered context + evidence-first selection + strict budgets.

A “better than Copilot-like” context architecture (for Volt)

Tier 0 — Live editor state (highest priority)

Active file path, language, dirty state
Current selection (range + text)
Cursor position
Open tabs list
Why: this is what the user means right now.
Tier 1 — Local evidence (cheap + reliable)

workspace.search results for the exact symbols/strings in the request
diagnostics.getProblems for current errors
projectMap.read() (entrypoints/scripts/routes)
Why: prevents hallucinated files and wrong assumptions.
Tier 2 — Semantic index (fast on big repos)

index.querySymbols, index.findReferences
import graph / symbol definitions
Why: “find the right files quickly” without reading everything.
Tier 3 — On-demand file reads

Pull only the smallest slices needed:
200–400 lines around matches/diagnostics
relevant config files (tsconfig/vite config)
Why: avoids dumping entire files into the model.
Tier 4 — External docs (MCP Context7)

Only when you’re touching external APIs or uncertain behavior.
Why: stops “guessing”.
Core rules that make it work

Hard token budget + packing order
Always pack: selection → local evidence → minimal file slices → index summaries → docs.
Evidence-first
If the agent can’t point to a file path + snippet that supports a claim, it should go fetch it.
“Context is a product”
Show the user exactly what’s attached (like Cursor): selection + files + diagnostics + search hits.
Let user remove attachments before sending.
